solar maximum mission

00:42.380 --> 00:51.800
satellite which was retrieved and repaired in orbit during a recent space
shuttle mission Solar Max's seven scientific instruments are constantly looking

00:51.800 --> 01:01.400
at the sun in search of clues that will help scientists understand solar flares
and other solar phenomena. Project scientist for Solar Maximum Mission is Dr.

01:01.820 --> 01:11.780
Bruce Woodgate. Solar flares. These are very large explosions on the sun which
occur in magnetic loops. They're a magnetic structure sticking up out of the

01:11.780 --> 01:23.880
sun, usually forming closed loops in active regions on the sun, around sunspots.
Also, there are open field regions which are called coronal holes and these are

01:23.880 --> 01:33.080
the origin of the solar wind, which streams out into the Earth's environment and
hits the Earth and cause magnetic storms when they switch over from one magnetic

01:33.080 --> 01:42.220
polarity to another. Solar Max gathered a wealth of information until it lost
its ability to point with fine precision at the Sun. The successful Solar

01:42.220 --> 01:51.120
Maximum Repair Mission last April not only demonstrated the shuttle's capability
to service satellites in space, but it also revived the most ambitious and

01:51.120 --> 02:01.500
successful solar flare research ever attempted. Shortly after its repair,
SolarMax detected the largest solar flares seen by any instrument. Right after

02:01.500 --> 02:10.560
the repair we did see extreme activity. The primary mission is still to find out
the physics of flares and see if we can find out anything about their

02:10.560 --> 02:19.680
predictability, about the buildup to when a flare would occur, what their
triggering mechanisms are. Scientists also want to understand more about the

02:19.680 --> 02:30.240
relationship between the sun and the earth. As both flares and active
prominences erupt out of the sun, they give rise to mass ejections from the

02:30.240 --> 02:37.560
corona. Pieces of the corona blast off and go into the solar wind, and they
travel along magnetic field lines, through the solar wind, and some of them will

02:37.560 --> 02:46.700
hit the earth and give rise to large magnetic storms. These disturbances can
trigger dramatic environmental effects. Auroras streak the skies in the northern

02:46.700 --> 02:57.140
latitudes. Radio communications are garbled. Surges in power lines can cut off
electricity and darken entire cities. And orbiting spacecraft and astronauts are

02:57.140 --> 03:05.940
endangered. Scientists would like to know more about solar flares in order to
forecast when and how unusual solar activity will affect the Earth's

03:05.940 --> 03:16.340
environment. Another area they're trying to understand is the solar cycle
itself. We want to look at the total solar flux, which appears to have been

03:16.340 --> 03:26.740
declining something like a tenth of a percent over the last four years from 1980
to 1984. If this decline were to occur and continue over many decades, it would

03:26.740 --> 03:38.980
eventually affect the climate on Earth. Another area of research is cometary
physics. We intend to observe Comet Halley in early 1986. For about two months,

03:39.040 --> 03:46.720
as the comet gets nearest to the Sun, where it's most active and most
interesting and brightest, it gets so close to the Sun that it can't be observed

03:46.720 --> 03:58.200
by telescopes from the ground or by other instruments from satellites, such as
the International Ultraviolet Explorer because it can't look closer than 45

03:58.200 --> 04:09.640
degrees to the Sun without burning itself out. But we intend to go off every
third orbit for about two months. So we'll have an observation about every four

04:09.640 --> 04:16.860
or five hours of the comet and go off and observe it, particularly with the
coronagraph instrument and see the structure of the tail. So that's interesting

04:16.860 --> 04:23.540
both for cometary physics and for the effects on the solar wind, or the effects
of the solar wind upon the comet.

