In January of this year, President Reagan directed NASA to begin the development
of a space station, setting a new goal in space for America. The space station

05:22.580 --> 05:31.180
will weigh approximately 40 tons, house six to eight men and women for up to six
months at a time, and offer living quarters somewhat larger than a one-bedroom

05:31.180 --> 05:39.980
apartment. The station will come equipped with scientific and industrial
laboratories, a satellite repair shop, a telescope platform for observing the

05:39.980 --> 05:50.560
sky, and another platform for looking back at Earth. It will also have a half
acre of solar cells furnishing 75 kilowatts of electric power. Dr. Robert

05:50.560 --> 05:59.040
Jastrow, former director of NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies and now a
professor at Dartmouth, believes that once the space station is in place,

05:59.240 --> 06:10.860
science gets a free ride on it. The most important scientific projects that NASA
has ever orbited, in my opinion, are the astronomical observatories. There are

06:10.860 --> 06:23.360
four of them, four great observatories. The Space Telescope, the advanced x-ray
observatory, Axaf, the gamma-ray observatory, and the advanced infrared

06:23.360 --> 06:36.840
observatory. And they're going up between about 1986 and the year 2000. Possibly
the most interesting projects in science in this century because they can

06:36.840 --> 06:46.820
reveal, give us information about how the universe came into being, they can see
out to the edge of space back into the beginning of time. With the space

06:46.820 --> 06:58.540
station, you can repair and refurbish these instruments in orbit. You can extend
their lifetime to many decades by taking out the instruments of the vintage of

06:58.540 --> 07:08.600
1980 or 1990 and installing new instruments at the focal point of the telescope
with electronics and devices that we don't even dream about now but that will

07:08.600 --> 07:19.320
exist in the year 2000. We asked Dr. Jastrow to explain how these observatories
will open new windows to the universe. the space telescope can see twice as far

07:19.320 --> 07:28.100
as telescopes on the ground even larger ones because the turbulence of the
earth's atmosphere does not blur its vision and it makes sharper images and

07:28.100 --> 07:36.500
therefore can see a fainter objects farther away if we can see out to the edge
view of the universe because light travels at a finite speed that's the same as

07:36.500 --> 07:44.420
seeing back to the moment of creation the so-called big bang the gamma ray
observatory will tell us something about gamma rays such as those produced by

07:44.420 --> 07:53.160
the annihilation of matter and antimatter. It'll be an insight which will point
us in some whole new direction towards perceiving the mysteries of the cosmos.

07:53.780 --> 08:04.640
The infrared observatory will reveal hidden objects in space dark objects. It
will tell us how stars and planets form." A space station could also serve as a

08:04.640 --> 08:15.280
staging area for assembling planetary missions. Alistair B. B. There are certain
flights to the planets of tremendous general interest which are too expensive to

08:15.280 --> 08:25.980
be done on a one-shot approach by direct descent from the ground. I have in mind
especially setting up a base on the moon for scientific observations and then

08:25.980 --> 08:37.380
carrying out an unmanned flight to Mars with the return of a surface sample. The
second mission will shed light on the question of Martian life, which was never

08:37.380 --> 08:47.020
satisfactorily resolved by Viking. There is another application of the station
that has commercial value and may also have great humanitarian importance. And

