10:29.780 --> 10:40.360
years of American manned space flight. The first occurred during the Gemini 6
mission in 1965. Jesse Moore is the acting Shuttle director at NASA Headquarters

10:40.360 --> 10:48.060
in Washington, DC. Jesse Moore, General Shuttle Director System We had a problem
with one of the valves in engine number three. The system immediately switched

10:48.060 --> 10:58.600
from channel A to the redundant channel B and started the operation. The general
purpose computer at that time, sensed that we didn't have full redundancy on

10:58.600 --> 11:08.020
each of the engines. So it started a shutdown sequence. That's the way the
system was designed. That's the way it's tested during the test programs. And

11:08.020 --> 11:18.200
our software system then begins an orderly shutdown of the engines. And at the
time the shutdown sequence occurs, we inhibit the ignition command to the solid

11:18.200 --> 11:25.780
rocket boosters so the shuttle doesn't lift off. The faulty engine has been
removed from Discovery and has gone through rigorous testing at NASA's National

11:25.780 --> 11:36.160
Space Technology Laboratories in Mississippi. We feel very confident that we
will be able to identify the problem that we had on the launch pad and that we

11:36.160 --> 11:47.360
have since put a new engine back into Discovery. And the engines we have on
Discovery now are the original engines that we had on board at the time we did a

11:47.360 --> 11:55.740
flight readiness firing back in the May time frame prior to our attempted launch
in June. So we feel very confident that the engines will work fine on this

11:55.740 --> 12:05.620
particular upcoming launch of Discovery. NASA is planning to combine the cargo
from what was to be the June flight, or 41D, and a second flight, originally

12:05.620 --> 12:14.580
slated for August 29th. The payloads and discoveries flight now include the
solar array, designed to study the possibilities of obtaining electrical power

12:14.580 --> 12:24.380
