14:44.100 --> 14:54.400
Back in 1980, a small California company was contracted by NASA to develop a new
type of safety net for use on the space shuttle. The net had to be fire

14:54.400 --> 15:04.380
-resistant and also strong. Nomex was the only flame-retardant material
available that would do the job, but it was not very strong. The nets had to

15:04.380 --> 15:15.300
withstand an impact of 3,500 pounds. Bill Kirkland, president of West Coast
Netting, continues this story. Those design criterias that we were faced with

15:15.300 --> 15:30.740
were very, very stringent because of the low tenacity fiber that we had. The
fiber being down in strength, 70% from nylon, 65% from polyester, was the real

15:30.740 --> 15:41.820
problem is how to get the net to work and to withstand the loads. In the process
of doing this, we have arrived with a new type of twisting for making twines,

15:41.840 --> 15:51.580
which under load will break evenly, as opposed to one of the three ends failing
by themselves, which has been what has been done in the past. By doing it this

15:51.580 --> 16:07.680
way, we have gained tensile strength of somewhere around 10%. We have tied that
manufacturing process to the fishing industry, and along with that have a new

16:07.680 --> 16:20.420
product called Hyperester, which is a high-density, high-specific gravity in the
polyester family fiber, and this product is designed to compete with what the

16:20.420 --> 16:31.720
Japanese or the average tuna net has been built out of for the last 25 years.
The Japanese net is composed of a tubular design material which must fill with

16:31.720 --> 16:44.620
water in order to sink. So consequently, it's not as efficient a tool as it
could be. The product that we have designed is a twisted product which has no

16:44.620 --> 16:56.000
voids in the middle of it. It's a high specific gravity product which means it
weighs 2.7 times more than nylon in the water and loses no tensile strength when

16:56.000 --> 17:09.240
it's wet. Production has been increased from 17 tons on an average per set to 55
tons, on an average, per set, this type of production is definitely significant.

17:10.820 --> 17:22.600
We have also had sets that have run up over four, five, up to 700 tons. With the
product we've got to learn how to fish all over again because of the production

17:22.600 --> 17:31.900
being so great. Because the American fishing industry has been facing rising
costs in equipment and fuel, it's been difficult to compete against foreign

17:31.900 --> 17:40.920
fishing fleets. The vessels are becoming more and more expensive. They're up
into the 10 million dollar range, and burning fuel, a million dollars worth of

17:40.920 --> 17:51.840
fuel a year. So we feel like this is definitely a significant gain. There's not
too many times that you come along and you can develop a product for an industry

17:51.840 --> 18:02.360
and show a gain factor of 20, 30 percent. We feel like that's a rather
conservative figure. Our production has continued to show us that we were

18:02.360 --> 18:12.320
averaging somewhere around three times more production than what the current net
is being used. What that means to the fishermen is that an 80-day trip is

18:12.320 --> 18:25.520
reduced down to 29 days. The 29 days versus the 80 days at 5,000 gallons of fuel
a day, just the fuel savings alone becomes monumental. Fishing Nets, a new space

18:25.520 --> 18:30.020
age spin-off with down-to-earth, down-to-the-sea applications.

